00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:46.960
And since we always feature our
winner at this Gala evening,

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:50.830
we offer you now a very
brief video on the life,

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:56.420
and work of Denis Johnson.

00:07:56.420 --> 00:08:01.240
&gt;&gt; English words are like
prisons, empty, nothing inside,

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:03.290
and still they make rainbows.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:06.540
So says a character in "Already
Dead", a Novel by the late,

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:09.200
great American writer,
Denis Johnson.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:14.030
Johnson's stories, as legions of
his fans know, are also prisons.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:20.190
They are hard, merciless, flinty,
and yet they too, make rainbows.

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:24.110 position:56%
He's been called a writer's writer's
writer, and for all the indigma

00:08:24.110 --> 00:08:27.880
of that string of words,
they hold a simple truth.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:32.820 position:56%
Those who bring language to life,
recognize Johnson's gifts instantly.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:37.200
Louise Erdrich calls his work
profound, and transcendent.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:42.270 position:56%
Jonathan Franzen finds his sentences
miracles of transparency and tone.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:46.640
Phillip Roth, calls him daring,
terrifying, and an emissary

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:48.650
for tortured, broken souls.

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:52.700
Marilyn Robinson marvels that
a writer's personal passions,

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:57.440
and energies, can be so
inextricably wedded to his words.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:01.350
All agree, Denis Johnson has
managed to give us minimalist,

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:07.270
yet distinctly ecstatic, and
hallucinatory rainbow probes.

00:09:07.270 --> 00:09:08.620
He is an American original.

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:13.280
He was born in 1949, in Munich,
Germany, and raised in Tokyo,

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:15.300
and Manila, the child
of American diplomats.

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:18.470
As a teenager, moving
back to Washington D.C.,

00:09:18.470 --> 00:09:21.710
during the tumultuous 60's,
he came to know the country,

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:25.250 position:56%
and the restless characters he would
capture so vividly in his fiction.

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:29.010 position:56%
He graduated in English
Literature, from University of Iowa,

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:32.240
and earned a MFA, from
the Iowa Writers Workshop,

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:33.540
where he returned as a teacher.

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:36.530
He has also taught
at Texas University,

00:09:36.530 --> 00:09:39.420
and the University
of Texas, at Austin.

00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:42.810
In the course of his favorite
career, he published novels,

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:45.670
short stories, journalism,
and poetry.

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:50.730
Among with his best works are
those about the Flotsam and Jetsam

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:55.000
of American Life, The
Laughing Monsters, Nobody Move,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:04.090
Tree of Smoke, Already Dead, Jesus'
Son, Resuscitation of a Hanged Man,

00:10:04.090 --> 00:10:07.000
The Stars at Noon,
Fiskadora, Angels.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.650
He's received numerous
awards for these,

00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:12.290
including a national book award,
a Lannan Fellowship in fiction,

00:10:12.290 --> 00:10:15.270
a writing writers award,
and in 2008,

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:18.570
he was named a finalist
for the Pulitzer Prize.

00:10:18.570 --> 00:10:22.380
Throughout, he has chronicled an
America that has gone unobserved,

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:28.850
unrecorded, here are our drug
addicts, our war veterans,

00:10:28.850 --> 00:10:31.870
our disaffected, our
used up and left behind,

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:35.850
and yet the most affecting,
and rewarding aspect

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:38.880
of Denis Johnson's fiction
is that in work, after work,

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:43.680
he has proved that beauty often
lurks in unexpected places,

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:46.470
that strength can be
found in failure,

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:51.070
that the human spirit is a
fragile, but resilient vessel.

00:10:51.070 --> 00:10:54.060
His is a very American Story.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:58.470
He once described his works as
pressure cookers of language,

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:01.110
his characters as those who
inhabit life's perilous edge.

00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:06.290
As time wore on, he found that
he himself was all too vulnerable

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:07.590
to these human frailties.

00:11:07.590 --> 00:11:10.380
When the Librarian of
Congress, Carla Hayden,

00:11:10.380 --> 00:11:14.220 position:56%
offered Denis Johnson the Library of
Congress Prize for American Fiction,

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:19.300
in March of 2017, he
wrote in an email message,

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:23.670
"My head is spinning
from such great news".

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:26.620
Two months later, tragically,
he was dead.

00:11:26.620 --> 00:11:29.220
The Library is very proud
to honor, posthumously,

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:32.980
this extraordinary human being,
and writer, who's contributions

00:11:32.980 --> 00:11:36.330
to the American can and have
been been lasting and invaluable.

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:41.970 position:56%
As the Librarian wrote, when the
prize was announced in June of 2017,

00:11:41.970 --> 00:11:46.400
Denis Johnson was a writer for our
times, in prose that fused grace

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:50.720
with wit, he spun tale after
tale about our walking wounded,

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:53.300
the demons that haunt,
the salvation we seek.

00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:58.400
We emerge from his imagined
world, with profound empathy,

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:00.400
a different perspective,
a little changed.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:04.400
We're very proud to count Denis
Johnson among the distinguished

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:14.510
winners of the Library of Congress
Prize for American Fiction.

