00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:29.340
&gt;&gt; People who can read, and
do, are healthier, happier,

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:32.510
and live longer than
people who can't.

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:35.760
They are more likely to get
preventative health care,

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:39.140
and are less likely to
go to an emergency room.

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:42.830
Women and girls who are
educated, have fewer children,

00:14:42.830 --> 00:14:46.640
and those they do have, are
twice as likely to survive.

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:49.840
Everyone benefits from literacy.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:53.660
For every one percent increase
in a country's literacy rate,

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:57.410
there is a permanent
1.5 percent increase

00:14:57.410 --> 00:15:00.730
in it's gross domestic product.

00:15:00.730 --> 00:15:09.090
But illiteracy is widespread,
worldwide 758 million adults,

00:15:09.090 --> 00:15:15.110
most of them women, cannot read
or write a simple sentence.

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:19.250
Illiteracy contributes
to poverty, and crime.

00:15:19.250 --> 00:15:24.860 position:56%
43 percent of adults with the lowest
literacy levels, live in poverty.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:29.740
70 percent of adult welfare
recipients have trouble reading.

00:15:29.740 --> 00:15:36.220
75 percent of state prison inmates
did not complete high school.

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:38.910
Illiteracy is expensive,

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:45.500
low literacy cost the U.S.
225 billion dollars each year

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:50.390
in lost work force productivity,
crime, and unemployment.

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:57.310
And illiteracy cost the global
economy 1.19 trillion each year.

